One great reason why Plautus’ lines are hard to scan is that he lived earlier than Ennius, who introduced most of the metrica] laws by which classical Latin poetry is bound, and who gave the Latin language a distinct literary shape. Ennius, for instance, made it a usage of Latin poetry that a short vowel might be treated as long before two consonants‚ such as crin the middle of a word. This usage was unknown to Plautus, and so in his lines such a word as sacrum is never scanned sacrum. Again, in Ennius’ time the consonants‚ m, s, t, n, d and others, were often hardly sounded at the end of a word.
